WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:12.723 --> 00:00:19.624
(Clicking)
（滴答声）

2
00:00:19.624 --> 00:00:24.240
I was born with bilateral retinoblastoma,
我出生时双眼都有眼癌，

3
00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:26.173
retinal cancer.
视网膜细胞瘤。

4
00:00:27.133 --> 00:00:30.239
My right eye was removed
我右眼在

5
00:00:30.239 --> 00:00:33.156
at seven months of age.
我7个月大时移除。

6
00:00:33.156 --> 00:00:36.873
I was 13 months when they removed my left eye.
13个月大时，左眼移除。

7
00:00:37.823 --> 00:00:42.968
The first thing I did upon awakening from that last surgery
我从手术中醒来做的第一件事

8
00:00:42.968 --> 00:00:46.600
was to climb out of my crib
就是爬出我的婴儿床，

9
00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:50.709
and begin wandering around the intensive care nursery,
开始在加强监护婴儿室东跑西跑，

10
00:00:51.649 --> 00:00:55.028
probably looking for the one who did this to me.
可能在寻找那个把我弄成这样的人。

11
00:00:55.028 --> 00:00:56.886
(Laughter)
（笑声）

12
00:00:58.786 --> 00:01:01.947
Evidently, wandering around the nursery
显然，在婴儿室东跑西跑

13
00:01:01.947 --> 00:01:05.522
was not a problem for me without eyes.
对于没有双眼的我来说并不是难题。

14
00:01:05.522 --> 00:01:08.157
The problem was getting caught.
难题是不被抓住。

15
00:01:09.377 --> 00:01:12.551
It's impressions about blindness
对于失明的印象

16
00:01:12.551 --> 00:01:16.041
that are far more threatening
远比失明本身

17
00:01:16.041 --> 00:01:19.573
to blind people than the blindness itself.
让盲人更恐惧。

18
00:01:21.103 --> 00:01:25.050
Think for a moment about your own impressions of blindness.
想想自己对于失明的印象。

19
00:01:25.050 --> 00:01:29.116
Think about your reactions when I first came onto the stage,
当我刚上台时，想想你们的反应，

20
00:01:29.116 --> 00:01:33.167
or the prospect of your own blindness,
或者想想你自己失明，

21
00:01:33.167 --> 00:01:37.084
or a loved one going blind.
或者爱的人将失明的景象。

22
00:01:37.084 --> 00:01:42.524
The terror is incomprehensible to most of us,
对于我们大多数人来说， 这都是难以想象的恐怖，

23
00:01:42.524 --> 00:01:44.979
because blindness
因为失明

24
00:01:44.979 --> 00:01:50.649
is thought to epitomize ignorance and unawareness,
被认为是无知无觉的缩影，

25
00:01:50.649 --> 00:01:58.450
hapless exposure to the ravages of the dark unknown.
不幸地暴露在未知黑暗的残迹之中。

26
00:01:58.450 --> 00:02:00.280
How poetic.
多么富有诗意。

27
00:02:01.260 --> 00:02:04.621
Fortunately for me, my parents were not poetic.
幸运的是，我的父母没有诗意。

28
00:02:04.621 --> 00:02:06.496
They were pragmatic.
他们很实际。

29
00:02:06.496 --> 00:02:13.113
They understood that ignorance and fear were but matters of the mind,
他们明白：无知和恐惧 仅仅是大脑精神层面的问题，

30
00:02:13.113 --> 00:02:17.102
and the mind is adaptable.
并且这种想法是可以改变的。

31
00:02:17.102 --> 00:02:20.803
They believed that I should grow up
他们相信我会长大

32
00:02:20.803 --> 00:02:25.634
to enjoy the same freedoms and responsibilities as everyone else.
享受和其他人一样的自由与责任。

33
00:02:25.634 --> 00:02:28.095
In their own words, I would move out --
用他们的话说，我会独立居住，

34
00:02:28.095 --> 00:02:30.882
which I did when I was 18 --
我18岁时做到了，

35
00:02:30.882 --> 00:02:32.855
I will pay taxes --
我将交税。

36
00:02:32.855 --> 00:02:35.695
thanks -- (Laughter) --
谢谢 （笑声）

37
00:02:37.425 --> 00:02:42.606
and they knew the difference between love and fear.
他们知道爱和恐惧的区别。

38
00:02:42.606 --> 00:02:47.530
Fear immobilizes us in the face of challenge.
面对挑战的时候，恐惧惊住了我们。

39
00:02:47.530 --> 00:02:50.432
They knew that blindness would pose a significant challenge.
他们知道失明是个巨大的挑战。

40
00:02:50.432 --> 00:02:53.486
I was not raised with fear.
我并不是在恐惧中成长。

41
00:02:53.486 --> 00:02:57.235
They put my freedom first before all else,
他们把我的自由 看得比其他东西都重要，

42
00:02:57.235 --> 00:03:00.355
because that is what love does.
因为那就是爱。

43
00:03:00.355 --> 00:03:04.584
Now, moving forward, how do I manage today?
继续讲，如今我是怎么生存的？

44
00:03:05.864 --> 00:03:09.239
The world is a much larger nursery.
世界是个大得多的育儿室。

45
00:03:09.239 --> 00:03:13.140
Fortunately, I have my trusty long cane,
幸运的是我有一支值得信赖的长手杖，

46
00:03:13.140 --> 00:03:15.834
longer than the canes used by most blind people.
比其他盲人的手杖更长。

47
00:03:15.834 --> 00:03:19.177
I call it my freedom staff.
我称它为我的自由帮手。

48
00:03:19.177 --> 00:03:20.733
It will keep me, for example,
例如，它能阻止我

49
00:03:20.733 --> 00:03:26.349
from making an undignified  departure from the stage. (Laughter)
不优雅的离开讲台。（笑声）

50
00:03:27.099 --> 00:03:29.062
I do see that cliff edge.
我确实看到峭边。

51
00:03:30.102 --> 00:03:33.329
They warned us earlier that every imaginable mishap
他们之前提醒我：

52
00:03:31.839 --> 00:03:36.920
has occurred to speakers up here on the stage.
演讲者在台上遇到过各种意外。

53
00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:38.941
I don't care to set a new precedent.
我不介意造一个新的意外。

54
00:03:40.311 --> 00:03:42.245
But beyond that,
但是除此之外，

55
00:03:42.245 --> 00:03:45.372
many of you may have heard me clicking as I came onto the stage --
大家在我来到讲台的时候， 听到我发出滴答声，

56
00:03:45.372 --> 00:03:46.439
(Clicking) --
（滴答声）

57
00:03:46.439 --> 00:03:48.308
with my tongue.
用舌头发的声音。

58
00:03:48.308 --> 00:03:51.486
Those are flashes of sound
那些都是声音的反射，

59
00:03:51.486 --> 00:03:56.566
that go out and reflect from surfaces all around me,
从所有我身边事物的表面反射回来，

60
00:03:56.566 --> 00:03:57.938
just like a bat's sonar,
就像一个蝙蝠的声呐，

61
00:03:57.938 --> 00:04:03.558
and return to me with patterns,  with pieces of information,
反馈给我一些信息，

62
00:04:03.558 --> 00:04:06.045
much as light does for you.
就像光反馈给你们信息一样。

63
00:04:06.955 --> 00:04:10.613
And my brain, thanks to my parents,
感谢我的父母，我的大脑

64
00:04:10.613 --> 00:04:15.918
has been activated to form images in my visual cortex,
能够在我的视觉皮质中筑构影像，

65
00:04:15.918 --> 00:04:19.158
which we now call the imaging system,
这就是我们所谓的成像系统，

66
00:04:19.158 --> 00:04:23.108
from those patterns of information, much as your brain does.
借助信息的结构形成图像， 就像你们的大脑。

67
00:04:23.108 --> 00:04:25.674
I call this process flash sonar.
我称这个过程为“闪光声呐”。

68
00:04:26.424 --> 00:04:32.142
It is how I have learned to see through my blindness,
我就是这样学会 在失明中去看见东西，

69
00:04:32.142 --> 00:04:35.318
to navigate my journey
为我导航，

70
00:04:35.318 --> 00:04:39.358
through the dark unknowns of my own challenges,
穿过挑战性的未知黑暗，

71
00:04:39.358 --> 00:04:43.259
which has earned me the moniker
我也因此得了一个绰号

72
00:04:43.259 --> 00:04:46.974
"the remarkable Batman."
“神奇蝙蝠侠”。

73
00:04:46.974 --> 00:04:49.528
Now, Batman I will accept.
我接受蝙蝠侠这个称号。

74
00:04:49.528 --> 00:04:52.918
Bats are cool. Batman is cool.
蝙蝠很有型，蝙蝠侠很酷。

75
00:04:52.918 --> 00:04:58.586
But I was not raised to think of myself as in any way remarkable.
但是我的成长教育并让我不觉得 自己任何一方面有什么奇特的。

76
00:04:59.676 --> 00:05:03.704
I have always regarded myself much like anyone else
我总是把自己看得和普通人一样，

77
00:05:03.704 --> 00:05:09.120
who navigates the dark unknowns of their own challenges.
他们也是在挑战性的 未知黑暗中自我摸索。

78
00:05:09.120 --> 00:05:12.538
Is that so remarkable?
这有很奇特吗？

79
00:05:12.538 --> 00:05:15.834
I do not use my eyes, I use my brain.
我不用双眼，我用的是大脑。

80
00:05:16.654 --> 00:05:19.137
Now, someone, somewhere,
此时某地的某人，

81
00:05:19.137 --> 00:05:22.964
must think that's remarkable, or I wouldn't be up here,
一定在想那的确很奇特， 否则我不会在这里，

82
00:05:22.964 --> 00:05:26.003
but let's consider this for a moment.
但是我们思考一下，

83
00:05:26.833 --> 00:05:29.559
Everyone out there
在场的所有人，

84
00:05:29.559 --> 00:05:34.248
who faces or who has ever faced a challenge,
正面对、或曾经面对过挑战的，

85
00:05:34.248 --> 00:05:35.980
raise your hands.
举起你们的手。

86
00:05:37.290 --> 00:05:39.310
Whoosh. Okay.
呼--。好的。

87
00:05:39.310 --> 00:05:42.282
Lots of hands going up, a moment, let me do a head count.
好多手，等一下，我数一下。

88
00:05:42.282 --> 00:05:44.323
(Clicking)
（滴答声）

89
00:05:45.533 --> 00:05:48.551
This will take a while. (Clicking) (Laughter)
这需要一会儿。 （滴答声）（笑声）

90
00:05:48.551 --> 00:05:50.025
Okay, lots of hands in the air.
好，空中好多手。

91
00:05:50.025 --> 00:05:52.429
Keep them up. I have an idea.
一直举着。我有个主意。

92
00:05:52.429 --> 00:05:58.122
Those of you who use your brains to navigate these challenges,
你们用大脑去克服挑战的人

93
00:05:58.122 --> 00:06:01.063
put your hands down.
放下你们的手。

94
00:06:02.243 --> 00:06:04.844
Okay, anyone with your hands still up
好的，仍然举着手的人

95
00:06:04.844 --> 00:06:10.082
has challenges of your own. (Laughter)
要挑战的是你自己。（笑声）

96
00:06:10.082 --> 00:06:12.659
So we all face challenges,
我们都面对挑战，

97
00:06:12.659 --> 00:06:16.397
and we all face the dark unknown,
我们都面对未知的黑暗，

98
00:06:16.397 --> 00:06:20.740
which is endemic to most challenges, which is what most of us fear, okay?
大部分挑战都是这样， 这也是我们的畏惧之处，对吗？

99
00:06:20.740 --> 00:06:24.593
But we all have brains
但是我们都有大脑

100
00:06:24.593 --> 00:06:28.889
that allow us, that activate to allow us
大脑让我们能够

101
00:06:28.889 --> 00:06:35.276
to navigate the journey through these challenges. Okay?
在挑战中摸索前进。

102
00:06:35.971 --> 00:06:40.104
Case in point: I came up here
很好的例子：我来到这里

103
00:06:40.104 --> 00:06:47.074
and -- (Clicking) -- they wouldn't tell me
（滴答声）他们不会告诉我，

104
00:06:47.074 --> 00:06:49.972
where the lectern was.
讲台在哪里。

105
00:06:49.972 --> 00:06:52.886
So you can't trust those TED folks.
不能相信TED的工作人员。

106
00:06:54.616 --> 00:06:56.473
"Find it yourself," they said.
“自己找，”他们说。

107
00:06:56.473 --> 00:06:59.883
So -- (Laughter)
所以--（笑声）

108
00:07:01.233 --> 00:07:04.345
And the feedback for the P.A. system is no help at all.
而且广播系统的反馈也无济于事。

109
00:07:04.345 --> 00:07:07.754
So now I present to you a challenge.
我要向你们展现一个挑战。

110
00:07:07.754 --> 00:07:11.670
So if you'd all close your eyes for just a moment, okay?
你们都闭上眼睛一会儿， 好吗？

111
00:07:11.670 --> 00:07:15.327
And you're going to learn a bit of flash sonar.
你们也将学会一点闪光声呐。

112
00:07:15.327 --> 00:07:16.837
I'm going to make a sound.
我会发出声响。

113
00:07:16.837 --> 00:07:20.382
I'm going to hold this panel in front  of me, but I'm not going to move it.
我会我面前举着这块平板， 我不会移动这块板。

114
00:07:20.382 --> 00:07:23.306
Just listen to the sound for a moment.
听一会儿。

115
00:07:25.056 --> 00:07:31.048
Shhhhhhhhhh.
“嘘-----------”

116
00:07:31.048 --> 00:07:33.113
Okay, nothing very interesting.
好吧，没什么特别。

117
00:07:33.113 --> 00:07:35.852
Now, listen to what happens to that same exact sound
现在听一听我移动平板

118
00:07:35.852 --> 00:07:37.636
when I move the panel.
发出的一样的声响。

119
00:07:38.966 --> 00:07:44.931
Shhhhhhhhhhh.  (Pitch getting higher and lower)
“嘘------------” （音调时高时低）

120
00:07:50.086 --> 00:07:53.429
You do not know the power of the dark side.
你们不了解黑暗的能量。

121
00:07:53.429 --> 00:07:55.241
(Laughter)
（笑声）

122
00:07:55.241 --> 00:07:57.632
I couldn't resist.
我情不自已。

123
00:07:59.652 --> 00:08:02.299
Okay, now keep your eyes closed
好吧，继续闭着眼，

124
00:08:02.299 --> 00:08:04.147
because, did you hear the difference?
你们听到差别了吗？

125
00:08:04.147 --> 00:08:07.245
Okay. Now, let's be sure.
好吧，让我们确认一下。

126
00:08:07.245 --> 00:08:09.044
For your challenge,
你们的挑战是：

127
00:08:09.044 --> 00:08:14.128
you tell me, just say "now" when you hear the panel start to move.
我开始移动平板的时候， 你们就要告诉我“现在”。

128
00:08:14.128 --> 00:08:17.120
Okay? We'll relax into this.
好吗？放松。

129
00:08:19.980 --> 00:08:23.643
Shhhhhhh.
“嘘-----”

130
00:08:23.643 --> 00:08:25.708
Audience: Now. Daniel Kish: Good. Excellent.
观众：现在。 丹尼尔·基什: 很棒。

131
00:08:25.708 --> 00:08:27.201
Open your eyes.
睁开眼睛。

132
00:08:27.201 --> 00:08:31.735
All right. So just a few centimeters,
就移动了几厘米，

133
00:08:31.735 --> 00:08:33.865
you would notice the difference.
你们就注意到这种变化。

134
00:08:33.865 --> 00:08:36.308
You've experienced sonar.
你们已经感受到声呐了。

135
00:08:37.348 --> 00:08:40.367
You'd all make great blind people. (Laughter)
你们都是了不起的瞎子。 （笑声）

136
00:08:40.367 --> 00:08:43.060
Let's have a look at what can happen
让我们看看

137
00:08:43.060 --> 00:08:46.404
when this activation process
要是这个声呐激活过程

138
00:08:46.404 --> 00:08:50.931
is given some time and attention.
得到更多的时间和关注。

139
00:08:50.931 --> 00:08:54.112
(Video) Juan Ruiz: It's like you guys can see with your eyes
（视频）Juan Ruiz: 就像 你们可以用眼睛去看一样，

140
00:08:54.112 --> 00:08:57.317
and we can see with our ears.
我们可以用耳朵去看。

141
00:08:57.317 --> 00:09:00.381
Brian Bushway: It's not a matter of enjoying it more or less,
男：关键不是欣赏多与少。

142
00:09:00.381 --> 00:09:03.307
it's about enjoying it differently.
而是从不同角度去欣赏。

143
00:09:03.307 --> 00:09:06.349
Shawn Marsolais: It goes across. DK: Yeah.
女：穿过了。 DK:对。

144
00:09:06.349 --> 00:09:10.157
SM: And then it's gradually coming back down again.
女：再逐渐往下。

145
00:09:10.157 --> 00:09:11.770
DK: Yes! SM: That's amazing.
DK: 对！ 女：太奇妙了。

146
00:09:11.770 --> 00:09:16.066
I can, like, see the car. Holy mother!
我能看到汽车。圣母马利亚！

147
00:09:21.801 --> 00:09:23.868
J. Louchart: I love being blind.
男2：我喜欢变瞎子。

148
00:09:23.868 --> 00:09:27.536
If I had the opportunity, honestly, I wouldn't go back to being sighted.
真诚的说，如果有机会， 我不打算重见光明了。

149
00:09:27.536 --> 00:09:30.996
JR: The bigger the goal, the more obstacles you'll face,
男3：目标越大，你面对的障碍越多，

150
00:09:30.996 --> 00:09:33.597
and on the other side of that goal
在目标的另一边

151
00:09:33.597 --> 00:09:35.245
is victory.
就是胜利。

152
00:09:35.245 --> 00:09:40.400
[In Italian]
（意大利语）

153
00:09:40.400 --> 00:09:50.175
(Applause)
（掌声）

154
00:09:50.175 --> 00:09:54.065
DK: Now, do these people look terrified?
基什: 这些人看上去很恐惧吗？

155
00:09:54.065 --> 00:09:55.887
Not so much.
没那么恐惧。

156
00:09:55.887 --> 00:09:58.673
We have delivered activation training
我们已经传授激活训练，

157
00:09:58.673 --> 00:10:02.202
to tens of thousands of blind and sighted people from all backgrounds
给成千上万的盲人， 以及各行各业的正常人，

158
00:10:02.202 --> 00:10:04.640
in nearly 40 countries.
遍及40个国家。

159
00:10:04.640 --> 00:10:09.122
When blind people learn to see,
当盲人学会看见，

160
00:10:09.122 --> 00:10:12.140
sighted people seem inspired
可视的人似乎受到了启发，

161
00:10:12.140 --> 00:10:17.197
to want to learn to see their way better, more clearly, with less fear,
他们想要学会更好更清晰、 不畏惧地看清他们的路，

162
00:10:18.447 --> 00:10:24.353
because this exemplifies the immense capacity within us all
这证明了我们潜在的巨大能力，

163
00:10:24.353 --> 00:10:30.866
to navigate any type of challenge, through any form of darkness,
我们可以在任何黑暗和挑战中前行，

164
00:10:30.866 --> 00:10:34.152
to discoveries unimagined
发现无法想象的东西，

165
00:10:34.152 --> 00:10:39.515
when we are activated.
只要我们被激活。

166
00:10:39.515 --> 00:10:45.529
I wish you all a most activating journey.
我祝愿你们拥有一个激励的旅途。

167
00:10:45.529 --> 00:10:47.294
Thank you very much.
非常感谢。

168
00:10:47.294 --> 00:10:54.515
(Applause)
（掌声）

169
00:10:55.536 --> 00:10:57.982
Chris Anderson: Daniel, my friend.
安德森: 丹尼尔，我的朋友。

170
00:10:57.982 --> 00:11:03.117
As I know you can see, it's a spectacular standing ovation at TED.
我知道你看得到： Ted观众的喝彩声壮观持久。

171
00:11:03.117 --> 00:11:06.101
Thank you for an extraordinary talk.
谢谢你的出众演讲。

172
00:11:06.101 --> 00:11:11.350
Just one more question about your world, your inner world that you construct.
关于你的世界、你所建立的内心世界， 我还想问一个问题。

173
00:11:11.350 --> 00:11:16.915
We think that we have things in our world that you as a blind person don't have,
我们认为在我们的世界中 我们拥有盲人没有的事物，

174
00:11:16.915 --> 00:11:18.639
but what's your world like?
但是你的世界是怎样的？

175
00:11:18.639 --> 00:11:21.402
What do you have that we don't have?
你有我们没有的东西吗？

176
00:11:21.402 --> 00:11:24.537
DK: Three hundred and sixty-degree view,
基什：360度视角，

177
00:11:24.537 --> 00:11:28.438
so my sonar works about as well behind me as it does in front of me.
也就是说，我的声呐 在身后和身前都看得见。

178
00:11:28.438 --> 00:11:30.319
It works around corners.
在拐角处也可以管用。

179
00:11:30.319 --> 00:11:33.058
It works through surfaces.
也可以穿过物体表面。

180
00:11:34.268 --> 00:11:39.049
Generally, it's kind of a fuzzy three-dimensional geometry.
一般而言,这是模糊的三维几何世界。

181
00:11:39.049 --> 00:11:43.089
One of my students, who has now become an instructor,
我有过一名学生，现在已经成为教员了，

182
00:11:43.089 --> 00:11:46.015
when he lost his vision, after a few months
在他失明后的几个月，

183
00:11:46.015 --> 00:11:48.267
he was sitting in his three story house
他正坐在三层楼高的家里，

184
00:11:48.267 --> 00:11:52.284
and he realized that he could hear everything going on throughout the house:
发觉自己能听到屋子里 正在进行的一切：

185
00:11:52.284 --> 00:11:56.463
conversations, people in the kitchen, people in the bathroom,
厨房里、浴室里人们的谈话

186
00:11:56.463 --> 00:11:59.157
several floors away, several walls away.
几层之外，几墙之隔的声音。

187
00:11:59.157 --> 00:12:02.709
He said it was something like having x-ray vision.
他说就像拥有X射线一样的视力。

188
00:12:02.709 --> 00:12:06.331
CA: What do you picture that you're in right now?
安德森：你会怎样描绘现在身处的地方？

189
00:12:06.331 --> 00:12:09.350
How do you picture this theater?
你怎样描绘这个现场？

190
00:12:09.350 --> 00:12:14.853
DK: Lots of loudspeakers, quite frankly.
基什：坦白说，很多大声说话的人。

191
00:12:16.273 --> 00:12:20.529
It's interesting.  When people make a sound,
当人们发声的时候，很有趣。

192
00:12:20.529 --> 00:12:25.684
when they laugh, when they fidget, when they take a drink or blow their nose
当他们笑，当他们坐立不安， 当他们喝水，或者擤鼻子，

193
00:12:25.684 --> 00:12:28.377
or whatever, I hear everything.
不管是什么，我都能听到。

194
00:12:28.377 --> 00:12:31.558
I hear every little movement that every single person makes.
我听到人们的细微动作。

195
00:12:31.558 --> 00:12:34.321
None of it really escapes my attention,
从声呐的视角，

196
00:12:34.321 --> 00:12:36.175
and then, from a sonar perspective,
它们都在我的注意力之内，

197
00:12:36.175 --> 00:12:42.029
the size of the room, the curvature  of the audience around the stage,
房间的大小，观众绕讲台的曲率，

198
00:12:42.029 --> 00:12:45.667
it's the height of the room.
房间的高度。

199
00:12:45.667 --> 00:12:48.947
Like I say, it's all that kind  of three-dimensional surface geometry
就像我说的，

200
00:12:47.207 --> 00:12:50.364
all around me.
环绕我的三维平面几何世界。

201
00:12:50.364 --> 00:12:52.650
CA: Well, Daniel, you have done a spectacular job
安德森：丹尼尔, 你的演讲很棒，

202
00:12:52.650 --> 00:12:55.475
of helping us all see the world in a different way.
帮助我们用不同的方式看世界。

203
00:12:55.475 --> 00:12:57.645
Thanks so much for that, truly. DK: Thank you.
真诚的谢谢你。 基什：谢谢。

204
00:12:57.645 --> 00:13:02.034
(Applause)
（掌声）